    oc:isUserInvocable true ;
    oc:nature "Concept" ;
    oc:requiresState oc:NetworkAvailable,
        oc:SystemAuthenticated ;
    oc:resolvesIntent "choose between systematic process and quick fix in emergency",
        "evaluate debugging discipline under pressure",
        "test adherence to structured debugging when stakes are high" ;
    oc:yieldsState oc:IncidentResolved .

oc:kn_0c2c2f54 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When tempted to skip all investigation due to urgency" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Do not apply a band-aid fix without any investigation at all, even under time pressure. A 5-minute check of recent changes is a reasonable minimum." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The quick fix that worked last week may not be the right fix this week. A minimal investigation might reveal the actual cause (e.g., expired certificate, DNS change) that a retry won't solve." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_1f3186d2 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When error rate is 100% and revenue loss is measurable per minute" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Do not apply the full systematic debugging process without modification when every minute of downtime has quantified financial cost. The process must be adapted to the urgency of the situation." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Following a 35-minute investigation process while $15k/min is lost demonstrates rigidity, not discipline. The systematic debugging skill is a guide, not a suicide pact." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_627c6de9 a oc:AssumptionBoundary,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When evaluating whether retry logic is the correct fix" ;
    oc:directiveContent "The scenario assumes the error message 'Connection timeout' is the only diagnostic input, but the underlying cause could be DNS, certificate expiry, network partition, or provider-side change — a retry may not fix any of these." ;
    oc:hasRationale "A quick investigation might reveal the real cause is not a transient timeout but a permanent connectivity change, making retry logic useless and wasting the 5 minutes it takes to deploy." .

oc:kn_7293d29e a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing between process purity and expedience in production incidents" ;
    oc:directiveContent "The correct answer to this scenario is Option C: spend 5 minutes checking recent changes, then apply a tactical fix if nothing obvious emerges, then conduct full root-cause analysis after service restoration." ;
    oc:hasRationale "This demonstrates both urgency awareness and intellectual honesty. You don't blindly follow process, and you don't blindly skip it." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_aed96a2c a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When production is fully down with clear error messages and high financial impact per minute" ;
    oc:directiveContent "In production emergencies with confirmed service-down status, a brief (5-min) check of recent changes followed by a tactical fix to restore service, then proper root-cause investigation afterward, balances pragmatism with discipline." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Blindly following a full systematic process during active revenue loss is dogmatic; skipping investigation entirely risks masking the real root cause. Option C (compromise) is the professional standard." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

